## Limitations

**Proxy methodology.** Population group labels are assigned using author-reported study population demographics and, as a fallback, author institutional affiliation geography. These are imperfect proxies — institutional geography does not equal researcher race or ethnicity, and many papers do not clearly report study population ancestry.

**Single item per gene-drug pair.** The current release contains one benchmark item per gene-drug pair. Both pool-condition models tested scored perfectly on straightforward items, suggesting harder items are needed where models must selectively weight non-European evidence even with full pool access. This is a known limitation to be addressed in future releases.

**Coverage auto-scoring.** Citation detection uses author last name + year pattern matching, which can fail on unusual name formats or when models paraphrase rather than cite. All auto-scores should be spot-checked against the actual response text.

**Equity flag and universality error require human review.** These two rubric dimensions cannot be reliably automated without a secondary judge model, and even then require human validation on a calibration set.

**Scope.** PGEquiCite covers pharmacogenomics specifically. The citation equity problem it measures likely extends to other biomedical domains, but this dataset does not cover them.

